Question:
According to the figure, when \(A\) and \(B\) are linked, which group is isomorphic to \(\pi_1(\mathbb{R}^3 \setminus (A \cup B))\)?

Options:
A: \(\mathbb{Z}\)
B: \(\mathbb{Z} * \mathbb{Z}\)
C: \(\mathbb{Z} \times \mathbb{Z}\)
D: \(SO(3)\)
E: \\

message.content:
When two circles \(A\) and \(B\) in \(\mathbb{R}^3\) are linked once (a standard Hopf link), the complement \(\mathbb{R}^3 \setminus (A \cup B)\) has fundamental group isomorphic to \(\mathbb{Z} \times \mathbb{Z}\). This can be seen by noticing the complement is homeomorphic to a torus times an interval, whose fundamental group is the fundamental group of the torus, \(\pi_1(T^2) \cong \mathbb{Z}^2\).

Answer:C
